SUMMARY:🔥 AU ABS: Labour Force\, Australia\, April 2026
DESCRIPTION:Source: AU ABS\nImpact: high\nSource: AU ABS\nImpact: high\nS
 ource: AU ABS\nImpact: high\nOfficial ABS latest release page\n\nExplain
 er:\n• What it is: Employment / Payrolls / Labour Force\n\n• Measure
 s: Change in employment\, unemployment\, participation and labour-market
  strength.\n\n• Usual market effect: Stronger-than-forecast jobs data 
 is usually bullish for the local currency and bearish for bonds if it in
 creases rate-hike expectations.\n\n• Why traders care: Jobs data is a 
 major driver of interest-rate expectations\, consumer spending expectati
 ons and recession-risk pricing.\n\n• Frequency: Monthly.\n\n• Notes:
  For the US\, Non-Farm Payrolls is one of the most market-moving release
 s. For Australia\, Labour Force data is important for RBA expectations.\
 n\n• Acronyms: NFP = Non-Farm Payrolls\; ABS = Australian Bureau of St
 atistics\; BLS = Bureau of Labor Statistics.\n\nOfficial source: https:/
 /www.abs.gov.au/statistics/labour/employment-and-unemployment/labour-for
 ce-australia/apr-2026\n\nExplainer:\n• What it is: Employment / Payrol
 ls / Labour Force\n\n• Measures: Change in employment\, unemployment\,
  participation and labour-market strength.\n\n• Usual market effect: S
 tronger-than-forecast jobs data is usually bullish for the local currenc
 y and bearish for bonds if it increases rate-hike expectations.\n\n• W
 hy traders care: Jobs data is a major driver of interest-rate expectatio
 ns\, consumer spending expectations and recession-risk pricing.\n\n• F
 requency: Monthly.\n\n• Notes: For the US\, Non-Farm Payrolls is one o
 f the most market-moving releases. For Australia\, Labour Force data is 
 important for RBA expectations.\n\n• Acronyms: NFP = Non-Farm Payrolls
 \; ABS = Australian Bureau of Statistics\; BLS = Bureau of Labor Statist
 ics.\n\nOfficial source: https://www.abs.gov.au/statistics/labour/employ
 ment-and-unemployment/labour-force-australia/apr-2026\n\nExplainer:\n•
  What it is: Employment / Payrolls / Labour Force\n\n• Measures: Chang
 e in employment\, unemployment\, participation and labour-market strengt
 h.\n\n• Usual market effect: Stronger-than-forecast jobs data is usual
 ly bullish for the local currency and bearish for bonds if it increases 
 rate-hike expectations.\n\n• Why traders care: Jobs data is a major dr
 iver of interest-rate expectations\, consumer spending expectations and 
 recession-risk pricing.\n\n• Frequency: Monthly.\n\n• Notes: For the
  US\, Non-Farm Payrolls is one of the most market-moving releases. For A
 ustralia\, Labour Force data is important for RBA expectations.\n\n• A
 cronyms: NFP = Non-Farm Payrolls\; ABS = Australian Bureau of Statistics
 \; BLS = Bureau of Labor Statistics.\n\nOfficial source: https://www.abs
 .gov.au/statistics/labour/employment-and-unemployment/labour-force-austr
 alia/apr-2026
