 ource: AU ABS\nImpact: high\nOfficial ABS latest release page\n\nExplain
 er:\n• What it is: Consumer Price Index\n\n• Measures: Change in the
  prices paid by consumers for a basket of goods and services.\n\n• Usu
 al market effect: Higher-than-forecast inflation is usually bullish for 
 the local currency and bearish for bonds\, because markets may price in 
 higher interest rates.\n\n• Why traders care: CPI is one of the most w
 atched inflation indicators because it can quickly shift central-bank ra
 te expectations.\n\n• Frequency: US CPI is monthly. Australian CPI has
  both monthly indicator releases and quarterly CPI releases.\n\n• Note
 s: Core CPI removes volatile items such as food and energy to give a cle
 aner read on underlying inflation pressure.\n\n• Acronyms: CPI = Consu
 mer Price Index.\n\nOfficial source: https://www.abs.gov.au/statistics/e
 conomy/price-indexes-and-inflation/consumer-price-index-australia/apr-20
 26\n\nExplainer:\n• What it is: Consumer Price Index\n\n• Measures: 
 Change in the prices paid by consumers for a basket of goods and service
 s.\n\n• Usual market effect: Higher-than-forecast inflation is usually
  bullish for the local currency and bearish for bonds\, because markets 
 may price in higher interest rates.\n\n• Why traders care: CPI is one 
 of the most watched inflation indicators because it can quickly shift ce
 ntral-bank rate expectations.\n\n• Frequency: US CPI is monthly. Austr
 alian CPI has both monthly indicator releases and quarterly CPI releases
 .\n\n• Notes: Core CPI removes volatile items such as food and energy 
 to give a cleaner read on underlying inflation pressure.\n\n• Acronyms
 : CPI = Consumer Price Index.\n\nOfficial source: https://www.abs.gov.au
 /statistics/economy/price-indexes-and-inflation/consumer-price-index-aus
 tralia/apr-2026\n\nExplainer:\n• What it is: Consumer Price Index\n\n
 • Measures: Change in the prices paid by consumers for a basket of goo
 ds and services.\n\n• Usual market effect: Higher-than-forecast inflat
 ion is usually bullish for the local currency and bearish for bonds\, be
 cause markets may price in higher interest rates.\n\n• Why traders car
 e: CPI is one of the most watched inflation indicators because it can qu
 ickly shift central-bank rate expectations.\n\n• Frequency: US CPI is 
 monthly. Australian CPI has both monthly indicator releases and quarterl
 y CPI releases.\n\n• Notes: Core CPI removes volatile items such as fo
 od and energy to give a cleaner read on underlying inflation pressure.\n
 \n• Acronyms: CPI = Consumer Price Index.\n\nOfficial source: https://
 www.abs.gov.au/statistics/economy/price-indexes-and-inflation/consumer-p
 rice-index-australia/apr-2026
