SUMMARY:🔥 AU ABS: Consumer Price Index\, Australia
DESCRIPTION:Source: AU ABS\nImpact: high\nSource: AU ABS\nImpact: high\nS
 ource: AU ABS\nImpact: high\nSource: AU ABS\nImpact: high\nReference per
 iod\n\nExplainer:\n• What it is: Consumer Price Index\n\n• Measures:
  Change in the prices paid by consumers for a basket of goods and servic
 es.\n\n• Usual market effect: Higher-than-forecast inflation is usuall
 y bullish for the local currency and bearish for bonds\, because markets
  may price in higher interest rates.\n\n• Why traders care: CPI is one
  of the most watched inflation indicators because it can quickly shift c
 entral-bank rate expectations.\n\n• Frequency: US CPI is monthly. Aust
 ralian CPI has both monthly indicator releases and quarterly CPI release
 s.\n\n• Notes: Core CPI removes volatile items such as food and energy
  to give a cleaner read on underlying inflation pressure.\n\n• Acronym
 s: CPI = Consumer Price Index.\n\nOfficial source: https://www.abs.gov.a
 u/release-calendar/future-releases/202611\n\nExplainer:\n• What it is:
  Consumer Price Index\n\n• Measures: Change in the prices paid by cons
 umers for a basket of goods and services.\n\n• Usual market effect: Hi
 gher-than-forecast inflation is usually bullish for the local currency a
 nd bearish for bonds\, because markets may price in higher interest rate
 s.\n\n• Why traders care: CPI is one of the most watched inflation ind
 icators because it can quickly shift central-bank rate expectations.\n\n
 • Frequency: US CPI is monthly. Australian CPI has both monthly indica
 tor releases and quarterly CPI releases.\n\n• Notes: Core CPI removes 
 volatile items such as food and energy to give a cleaner read on underly
 ing inflation pressure.\n\n• Acronyms: CPI = Consumer Price Index.\n\n
 Official source: https://www.abs.gov.au/release-calendar/future-releases
 /202611\n\nExplainer:\n• What it is: Consumer Price Index\n\n• Measu
 res: Change in the prices paid by consumers for a basket of goods and se
 rvices.\n\n• Usual market effect: Higher-than-forecast inflation is us
 ually bullish for the local currency and bearish for bonds\, because mar
 kets may price in higher interest rates.\n\n• Why traders care: CPI is
  one of the most watched inflation indicators because it can quickly shi
 ft central-bank rate expectations.\n\n• Frequency: US CPI is monthly. 
 Australian CPI has both monthly indicator releases and quarterly CPI rel
 eases.\n\n• Notes: Core CPI removes volatile items such as food and en
 ergy to give a cleaner read on underlying inflation pressure.\n\n• Acr
 onyms: CPI = Consumer Price Index.\n\nOfficial source: https://www.abs.g
 ov.au/release-calendar/future-releases/202611\n\nExplainer:\n• What it
  is: Consumer Price Index\n\n• Measures: Change in the prices paid by 
 consumers for a basket of goods and services.\n\n• Usual market effect
 : Higher-than-forecast inflation is usually bullish for the local curren
 cy and bearish for bonds\, because markets may price in higher interest 
 rates.\n\n• Why traders care: CPI is one of the most watched inflation
  indicators because it can quickly shift central-bank rate expectations.
 \n\n• Frequency: US CPI is monthly. Australian CPI has both monthly in
 dicator releases and quarterly CPI releases.\n\n• Notes: Core CPI remo
 ves volatile items such as food and energy to give a cleaner read on und
 erlying inflation pressure.\n\n• Acronyms: CPI = Consumer Price Index.
 \n\nOfficial source: https://www.abs.gov.au/release-calendar/future-rele
 ases/202611
